Tuples -> ()
- Tuples are Immutable -> They cannot be changed
- Similar to Arrays, but immutable

```
masala_spices = ("Cardomom, "Cloves, "cinnamon")
(spice1, spice2, spice3) = masala_spices

//unpacking
print(f"Main Masala Spices: {spice1}, {spice2}, {spice3}") 



ginger_ratio, cardamom_ratio = 2,1
// 2 wil be alocated to gigner_ratio and 1 will be automatically allocated to cardamom_ratio
// This is possbile because of tuples, it converts the 2,1 into (2,1) [tuples] and assigns it to the variable.  

print(f"Ratio is G: {giner_ratio} and C: {Cardemom Ratio}")  // o/p : Ratio of G : 2 and C : 1
```

- We can flip the ratio/values without creating a temp variable, with the help of tuples

```
// This will put the value of cadramom value to the ginger value andd vice versa (Unique feature of python.)
ginger_ratio , cardramom_ratio = cadramom_ratio, ginger_raio

```

MEMBERSHIP TESTING

```
print(f"Is ginger in masala spices? {'ginger' in masala_spices}" // o/p : False
NOTE : ginger must be case sensitive
print(f"Is cinamon in masala spices? {'cinamon' in masala_spices}" // o/p : True
print(f"Is cinamon in masala spices? {'Cinamon' in masala_spices}" // o/p : Flase (case sensitive)
```

Membership testing is used to check whether the particular string or object or variable is present in the said tuple.

